Google, Samsung, Huawei sued for Nortel patents
The group, which includes thousands of former Nortel patents filed an avalanche of claims of patent infringement against mobile phone maker on Thursday, including Google, the company, which was outbid by him at the bankruptcy auction by Nortel.
Rockstar, the consortium that bought the Nortel patents for $ 4.5 billion, sued Samsung Electronics Co Ltd, HTC Corp, Huawei and four other companies for patent infringement in the US District Court in Texas.
Rockstar is community owned by Apple, Microsoft, BlackBerry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google is accused in seven cases of patent infringement.
The patents concern technology that bring search terms on the Internet with relevant advertising in accordance to the lawsuit, which goes to the heart of Google's search engine business to.
Representatives from Samsung, Huawei, HTC, and rock star were not immediately reachable.
Samsung, Huawei and HTC make cell phones that work with Google's operating system Android, which is in sharp competition with Apple's mobile products and Microsoft.
In 2011, Google issued an initial bid more than $900 million for the Nortel patents.
Google increased its offer several times and most recently offered $ 4.4 billion.
After it was outbid by Rockstar for the Nortel patents, Google Motorola mobility acquired for $ 12.5 billion, a deal that was also motivated partly by Motorola's library of patents.
"Although Google, failed in his attempt to acquire the claim patents at the auction, Google has infringed the patents and continues to do this", so the complaint letter.
Rock Star calls a high compensation from Google, because it claimed that Google's patent infringement is intentional, according to the accusation.
